This paper deals with the design and optimization of visible light communication (VLC) networks, which are a type of wireless network. The paper discusses various techniques for assigning LEDs to users, optimizing power control, and improving signal-to-interference-plus-noise-ratio (SINR) using multi-element receivers. These topics are all related to network optimization and signal processing, which are typically covered in the computer science sub-categories of cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture), cs.IT (Information Theory), and cs.SY (Systems and Control). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of LEDs for illumination, which falls under the sub-category of cs.MM (Multimedia). Finally, the paper discusses the use of existing lighting infrastructure, which is related to the sub-category of cs.CE (Computers and Society).
